<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">

  <title>Jason Cheng | Electrical Engineering Portfolio</title>

  <style>
    * {
      box-sizing: border-box;
    }

    body {
      margin: 0;
      font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
      background: #f4f6f8;
      color: #172033;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }

    header {
      background: #102a43;
      color: white;
      padding: 60px 20px;
      text-align: center;
    }

    header h1 {
      margin: 0;
      font-size: 42px;
    }

    header p {
      margin: 10px 0 0;
      font-size: 18px;
    }

    main {
      width: min(1050px, 90%);
      margin: 40px auto;
    }

    .project {
      background: white;
      border-radius: 12px;
      overflow: hidden;
      box-shadow: 0 4px 18px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
      margin-bottom: 40px;
    }

    .project-image {
      width: 100%;
      max-height: 620px;
      object-fit: cover;
      display: block;
    }

    .layout-image {
      object-fit: contain;
      background: #07182c;
      padding: 20px;
    }

    .project-content {
      padding: 30px;
    }

    .project-content h2 {
      margin-top: 0;
      margin-bottom: 12px;
      color: #102a43;
      font-size: 28px;
    }

    .project-content h3 {
      margin-top: 30px;
      margin-bottom: 12px;
      color: #102a43;
      font-size: 21px;
    }

    .project-content p {
      margin-top: 0;
      margin-bottom: 16px;
    }

    .tags {
      margin-top: 18px;
    }

    .tag {
      display: inline-block;
      background: #e3edf7;
      color: #102a43;
      padding: 5px 10px;
      margin: 3px;
      border-radius: 20px;
      font-size: 14px;
    }

    .button {
      display: inline-block;
      margin-top: 20px;
      padding: 11px 18px;
      background: #1769aa;
      color: white;
      text-decoration: none;
      border-radius: 6px;
      font-weight: bold;
    }

    .button:hover {
      background: #0f4f82;
    }

    .detail-image {
      width: 100%;
      display: block;
      margin: 15px 0 25px;
      border-radius: 8px;
      border: 1px solid #d9e0e7;
      background: #f7f9fb;
    }
    .project-video {
  width: 100%;
  max-height: 650px;
  object-fit: contain;
  display: block;
  margin: 15px 0 25px;
  border-radius: 8px;
  border: 1px solid #d9e0e7;
  background: #000;
}

.project-content ul {
  padding-left: 22px;
  margin-top: 0;
  margin-bottom: 20px;
}

.project-content li {
  margin-bottom: 8px;
}
    .image-gallery {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
      gap: 18px;
      margin-top: 15px;
    }

    .gallery-item {
      margin: 0;
    }

    .gallery-item img {
      width: 100%;
      height: 330px;
      object-fit: contain;
      display: block;
      background: #f7f9fb;
      border: 1px solid #d9e0e7;
      border-radius: 8px;
    }

    .gallery-item figcaption {
      margin-top: 7px;
      color: #5b677a;
      font-size: 14px;
      text-align: center;
    }

    footer {
      text-align: center;
      padding: 30px;
      color: #5b677a;
    }

    @media (max-width: 700px) {
      header h1 {
        font-size: 34px;
      }

      header {
        padding: 45px 18px;
      }

      .project-content {
        padding: 22px;
      }

      .project-content h2 {
        font-size: 24px;
      }

      .image-gallery {
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      }

      .gallery-item img {
        height: auto;
      }

      .project-image {
        max-height: none;
      }
    }
  </style>
</head>

<body>

  <header>
    <h1>Jason Cheng</h1>
    <p>Electrical Engineering Student at UC Santa Cruz</p>
  </header>

  <main>

    <!-- NTU RESEARCH PROJECT -->
    <section class="project">

      <img
        class="project-image"
        src="ntu-poster-preview.jpg"
        alt="Jason Cheng presenting the Quantized BERT on CIM Accelerators research poster at National Taiwan University"
      >

      <div class="project-content">

        <h2>Quantized BERT on CIM Accelerators</h2>

        <p>
          Conducted transformer quantization research at National Taiwan
          University by implementing quantization-aware training in PyTorch
          on a compact BERT model for INT8 inference. Evaluated the model
          across seven GLUE benchmark tasks while preserving hardware
          efficiency.
        </p>

        <p>
          Generated quantized weights, biases, and softmax lookup tables,
          then exported them as JSON files formatted for future integration
          with a 28 nm CMOS compute-in-memory transformer accelerator using
          bit-serial data streaming and SRAM-based matrix multiplication.
        </p>

        <div class="tags">
          <span class="tag">PyTorch</span>
          <span class="tag">BERT</span>
          <span class="tag">INT8 Quantization</span>
          <span class="tag">Compute-in-Memory</span>
          <span class="tag">Python</span>
          <span class="tag">Hardware-Aware AI</span>
        </div>

        <a
          class="button"
          href="./ntu-poster.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
        >
          View Research Poster
        </a>

      </div>

    </section>
    
<!-- HIGH-SPEED SIGNAL INTEGRITY PCB -->
<section class="project">

  <img
    class="project-image layout-image"
    src="highspeed-pcb-layout.png"
    alt="KiCad PCB layout for a high-speed signal integrity test board"
  >

  <div class="project-content">

    <h2>High-Speed Signal Integrity PCB</h2>

    <p>
      Designed and fabricated a KiCad PCB to experimentally demonstrate
      ground bounce, crosstalk, and channel loss. The board uses a
      74AHC241 8-bit buffer, capacitive output loading, adjacent parallel
      traces, and long serpentine traces to create measurable
      signal-integrity effects.
    </p>

    <p>
      The board was designed for testing with a 10 MHz, 5 V peak-to-peak
      input signal using an oscilloscope and spectrum analyzer. Test
      structures and coaxial connections were included to measure voltage
      spikes, coupled noise, rise-time degradation, and frequency-dependent
      signal loss.
    </p>

    <div class="tags">
      <span class="tag">KiCad</span>
      <span class="tag">PCB Design</span>
      <span class="tag">Signal Integrity</span>
      <span class="tag">Ground Bounce</span>
      <span class="tag">Crosstalk</span>
      <span class="tag">Channel Loss</span>
      <span class="tag">74AHC241</span>
      <span class="tag">Oscilloscope Testing</span>
    </div>

    <h3>Schematic</h3>

    <img
      class="detail-image"
      src="highspeed-schematic.png"
      alt="KiCad schematic for the high-speed signal integrity PCB"
    >

    <h3>PCB Design and Fabricated Board</h3>

    <div class="image-gallery">

      <figure class="gallery-item">
        <img
          src="highspeed-pcb-layout.png"
          alt="KiCad PCB layout showing ground bounce, crosstalk, and channel loss structures"
        >
        <figcaption>KiCad PCB layout</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure class="gallery-item">
        <img
          src="highspeed-board-front.png"
          alt="Front side of the fabricated high-speed signal integrity PCB"
        >
        <figcaption>Fabricated PCB — front side</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure class="gallery-item">
        <img
          src="highspeed-board-back.png"
          alt="Back side of the fabricated high-speed signal integrity PCB"
        >
        <figcaption>Fabricated PCB — back side</figcaption>
      </figure>

    </div>

  </div>

</section>
    <!-- AUDIO AMPLIFIER PROJECT -->
    <section class="project">

      <img
        class="project-image layout-image"
        src="audio-amplifier-pcb-layout.png"
        alt="Cadence Allegro PCB layout for a two-channel audio amplifier"
      >

      <div class="project-content">

        <h2>Audio Amplifier PCB</h2>

        <p>
          Designed a two-channel audio amplifier schematic in Cadence OrCAD
          Capture using LM324 operational amplifiers for input conditioning
          and gain control, followed by LM386 power-amplifier stages for
          driving external speakers.
        </p>

        <p>
          Created the PCB layout in Cadence Allegro, including component
          placement, custom footprints, signal routing, power distribution,
          spacing constraints, and design-rule verification. Completed DFM
          checks and generated Gerber and drill files for fabrication.
        </p>

        <div class="tags">
          <span class="tag">Cadence OrCAD</span>
          <span class="tag">Cadence Allegro</span>
          <span class="tag">PCB Design</span>
          <span class="tag">LM324</span>
          <span class="tag">LM386</span>
          <span class="tag">Gerber Files</span>
          <span class="tag">DFM</span>
        </div>

        <h3>Schematic</h3>

        <img
          class="detail-image"
          src="audio-amplifier-schematic.png"
          alt="Cadence OrCAD schematic for the two-channel audio amplifier"
        >

        <h3>PCB Layout and Manufacturing Output</h3>

        <div class="image-gallery">

          <figure class="gallery-item">
            <img
              src="audio-amplifier-pcb-layout.png"
              alt="Cadence Allegro PCB layout for the audio amplifier"
            >
            <figcaption>Cadence Allegro PCB layout</figcaption>
          </figure>

          <figure class="gallery-item">
            <img
              src="audio-amplifier-gerber.png"
              alt="Gerber and drill output for the audio amplifier PCB"
            >
            <figcaption>Gerber and drill-file review</figcaption>
          </figure>

          <figure class="gallery-item">
            <img
              src="audio-amplifier-board-top.jpg"
              alt="Top side of the fabricated audio amplifier PCB"
            >
            <figcaption>Fabricated PCB — top side</figcaption>
          </figure>

          <figure class="gallery-item">
            <img
              src="audio-amplifier-board-bottom.jpg"
              alt="Bottom side of the fabricated audio amplifier PCB"
            >
            <figcaption>Fabricated PCB — bottom side</figcaption>
          </figure>

        </div>

      </div>

    </section>
<!-- FPGA ARCADE GAME PROJECT -->
<section class="project">

  <img
    class="project-image"
    src="fpga-game-preview.png"
    alt="Arcade game running on a Basys 3 FPGA with VGA output"
  >

  <div class="project-content">

    <h2>FPGA Arcade Game with Real-Time VGA Graphics</h2>

    <p>
      Designed and implemented a hardware-based arcade game in structural
      Verilog on a Basys 3 Artix-7 FPGA. Built modular logic for VGA timing,
      player movement, pseudo-random apple spawning, independent ripeness
      timers, collision detection, score tracking, and lives management.
    </p>

    <p>
      Developed a 640 × 480, 60 Hz VGA graphics pipeline that mapped game
      state directly to RGB outputs with no software rendering. Created
      real-time pixel logic for the player, tree, apples, borders, and ground,
      along with timer-driven apple color changes and hardware-controlled
      game behavior.
    </p>

    <div class="tags">
      <span class="tag">Verilog</span>
      <span class="tag">FPGA</span>
      <span class="tag">Basys 3</span>
      <span class="tag">Artix-7</span>
      <span class="tag">VGA Graphics</span>
      <span class="tag">Vivado</span>
      <span class="tag">Collision Detection</span>
      <span class="tag">LFSR</span>
    </div>

    <h3>Hardware Demonstration</h3>

    <video
      class="project-video"
      controls
      poster="fpga-game-preview.png"
    >
      <source src="fpga-game-demo.mp4" type="video/mp4">
      Your browser does not support the video tag.
    </video>

    <h3>Key Features</h3>

    <ul>
      <li>
        Generated VGA synchronization and active-video timing for a
        640 × 480 display at 60 Hz.
      </li>

      <li>
        Implemented real-time pixel rendering for the player, apples,
        tree, ground, and screen boundaries.
      </li>

      <li>
        Used an LFSR and independent hardware timers to control apple
        positions, spawning, ripeness, and color changes.
      </li>

      <li>
        Developed hardware collision detection for catches and misses,
        along with score, lives, and game-over logic.
      </li>

      <li>
        Displayed game information using the Basys 3 seven-segment
        display and onboard LEDs.
      </li>
    </ul>

  </div>

</section>
  </main>

  <footer>
    © 2026 Jason Cheng
  </footer>

</body>
</html>
